284→  <main class="py-10 md:py-16">
285→    <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
286→
287→      <!-- Article Header -->
288→      <header class="mb-10">
289→        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
290→          <span class="inline-block bg-maroon/10 text-maroon text-xs font-semibold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide" data-i18n="blog.category.research">Research &amp; Frameworks</span>
291→          <time datetime="2026-02-10" class="text-sm text-gray-500">February 10, 2026</time>
292→        </div>
293→        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 leading-tight mb-6" data-i18n="blog.resilience.title">
294→          Rebuilding Resilience: Frameworks, Metrics, and Research for Communities and Individuals
295→        </h1>
296→        <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed" data-i18n="blog.resil.subtitle">
297→          A research compilation covering conceptual overviews, neighborhood-level frameworks, quantitative indices, and psychological resilience scales&mdash;tools for understanding, measuring, and strengthening resilience at every level.
298→        </p>
299→      </header>
300→      <figure class="mb-10">
301→        <picture>
302→          <source srcset="/blog/hero-rebuilding-resilience-640w.webp" media="(max-width: 768px)" type="image/webp">
303→          <source srcset="/blog/hero-rebuilding-resilience-1280w.webp" type="image/webp">
304→          <img src="/blog/hero-rebuilding-resilience.jpg" alt="Green seedling growing through cracked earth in morning sunlight" class="w-full rounded-lg shadow-md" width="1280" height="720" loading="eager">
305→        </picture>
306→      </figure>
307→
308→
309→      <!-- Article Body -->
310→      <div class="content-area prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-800 leading-relaxed">
311→
312→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p1">
313→          Resilience is used in several overlapping ways: as the capacity to withstand shocks, the dynamic process of adapting over time, and the outcomes that signal successful recovery or transformation. It helps to explicitly distinguish personal psychological resilience from community or neighborhood resilience, and then borrow concrete frameworks and metrics from each.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1" class="fn-ref">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn2" id="fnref2" class="fn-ref">[2]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn3" id="fnref3" class="fn-ref">[3]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn4" id="fnref4" class="fn-ref">[4]</a></sup>
314→        </p>
315→
316→        <hr>
317→
318→        <!-- BIG-PICTURE CONCEPTUAL OVERVIEWS -->
319→        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4" data-i18n="blog.resilience.h2.conceptual">Big-Picture Conceptual Overviews</h2>
320→
321→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p2">
322→          <strong>What Do We Mean by &ldquo;Community Resilience&rdquo;? A Systematic Literature Review of How It Is Defined and Measured</strong><br>
323→          Patel, S.S. et al. (2017) &mdash; <a href="https://currents.plos.org/disasters/article/what-do-we-mean-by-community-resilience-a-systematic-literature-review-of-how-it-is-defined-measured/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PLOS Currents Disasters</a><br>
324→          Synthesizes dozens of definitions and frameworks for community resilience, identifies common elements (local knowledge, networks, communication, governance, health), and discusses implications for practice and measurement.<sup><a href="#fn2" id="fnref2b" class="fn-ref">[2]</a></sup>
325→        </p>
326→
327→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p3">
328→          <strong>Resilience as Pathway Diversity: Linking Systems, Individual and Societal Resilience</strong><br>
329→          Lade, S.J. et al. (2019) &mdash; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.02294" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">arXiv</a><br>
330→          Proposes resilience as &ldquo;pathway diversity&rdquo; in social&ndash;ecological systems, giving language to talk about resilience as multiple possible futures rather than simply &ldquo;bouncing back.&rdquo;<sup><a href="#fn4" id="fnref4b" class="fn-ref">[4]</a></sup>
331→        </p>
332→
333→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p4">
334→          <strong>Community Resilience: A Multidisciplinary Exploration for Inclusive Frameworks</strong><br>
335→          (2024) &mdash; <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2772741624000085" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect</a><br>
336→          Provides an updated multidisciplinary review, clustering community resilience work into key themes (infrastructure, social capital, governance, equity), useful to structure essay sections and program design.<sup><a href="#fn5" id="fnref5" class="fn-ref">[5]</a></sup>
337→        </p>
338→
339→        <hr>
340→
341→        <!-- COMMUNITY AND NEIGHBORHOOD RESILIENCE FRAMEWORKS -->
342→        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4" data-i18n="blog.resilience.h2.community">Community and Neighborhood Resilience Frameworks</h2>
343→
344→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p5">
345→          <strong>EnRiCH Community Resilience Framework for High-Risk Populations</strong><br>
346→          O&rsquo;Sullivan, T.L. et al. (2014) &mdash; <a href="https://currents.plos.org/disasters/article/the-enrich-community-resilience-framework-for-high-risk-populations/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PLOS Currents Disasters</a><br>
347→          Puts &ldquo;adaptive capacity&rdquo; at the center, surrounded by four strategic areas (leadership, asset/resource management, awareness/communication, connectedness/engagement) driven by empowerment, innovation, and collaboration; helpful for describing levers neighborhoods can actually pull.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="fnref6" class="fn-ref">[6]</a></sup>
348→        </p>
349→
350→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p6">
351→          <strong>IFRC Framework for Community Resilience</strong><br>
352→          International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (2014) &mdash; <a href="https://www.ifrc.org/sites/default/files/IFRC-Framework-for-Community-Resilience-EN-LR.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PDF</a><br>
353→          Practice-oriented framework showing how to support communities to self-mobilize, strengthen local organizations, and link everyday well-being work to disaster resilience.<sup><a href="#fn7" id="fnref7" class="fn-ref">[7]</a></sup>
354→        </p>
355→
356→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p7">
357→          <strong>Creating the Conditions for Community Resilience</strong><br>
358→          <a href="https://doaj.org/article/336d60f2387247cd8b5ae1b20c6661f1" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DOAJ (open access)</a><br>
359→          Develops a conceptual framework summarizing common requirements for community resilience (e.g., social capital, inclusive governance, local capabilities), giving language for &ldquo;upstream&rdquo; neighborhood work beyond emergency planning.<sup><a href="#fn8" id="fnref8" class="fn-ref">[8]</a></sup>
360→        </p>
361→
362→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p8">
363→          <strong>Community Resilience to Pandemics: An Assessment Framework Integrating Social, Built and Natural Environments</strong><br>
364→          (2022) &mdash; <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9375855/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Europe PMC</a><br>
365→          Offers a concrete, indicator-based framework for assessing pandemic resilience at community scale, illustrating how to operationalize &ldquo;resilience&rdquo; in terms of environment, health systems, and social factors.<sup><a href="#fn9" id="fnref9" class="fn-ref">[9]</a></sup>
366→        </p>
367→
368→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p9">
369→          <strong>Community Resilience to Disasters: Measuring and Improving Community Resilience</strong><br>
370→          De Iuliis, M. et al. (2022) &mdash; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.04335" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">arXiv</a><br>
371→          Uses the PEOPLES framework (Population, Environmental, Organized governmental services, Physical infrastructure, Lifestyle, Economic, Social&ndash;cultural) with fuzzy logic to quantify resilience, useful as an example of making resilience computable.<sup><a href="#fn10" id="fnref10" class="fn-ref">[10]</a></sup>
372→        </p>
373→
374→        <hr>
375→
376→        <!-- QUANTITATIVE INDICES AND METRICS -->
377→        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4" data-i18n="blog.resilience.h2.metrics">Quantitative Indices and Metrics</h2>
378→
379→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p10">
380→          <strong>A Value-Focused Thinking Approach to Measure Community Sustainable Resilience</strong><br>
381→          Suresh, R. et al. (2024) &mdash; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.00901" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">arXiv</a><br>
382→          Builds an objectives hierarchy and indicators across social, economic, infrastructure, and environmental dimensions; reviews existing indices like the Community Disaster Resilience Index and Resilience Capacity Index, which can be referenced as examples of composite &ldquo;resilience scores.&rdquo;<sup><a href="#fn11" id="fnref11" class="fn-ref">[11]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn3" id="fnref3b" class="fn-ref">[3]</a></sup>
383→        </p>
384→
385→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p11">
386→          <strong>Deep Learning-Driven Community Resilience Rating Based on Social&ndash;Ecological&ndash;Technological Systems</strong><br>
387→          (Resili-Net, 2023) &mdash; <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2311.01661.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">arXiv</a><br>
388→          Develops a machine-learning rating system for urban resilience using features like infrastructure robustness, facility access, and social conditions, showing how newer work uses big data to map resilience across neighborhoods.<sup><a href="#fn12" id="fnref12" class="fn-ref">[12]</a></sup>
389→        </p>
390→
391→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p12">
392→          <strong>Development and Validation of a Community Resilience Scale for Youth</strong><br>
393→          Silva, S.M. et al. (2022) &mdash; <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0269027" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PLOS ONE</a><br>
394→          Provides a psychometrically validated survey to assess youths&rsquo; perception of community resilience; a good example of &ldquo;bottom-up&rdquo; measurement grounded in lived experience.<sup><a href="#fn13" id="fnref13" class="fn-ref">[13]</a></sup>
395→        </p>
396→
397→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p13">
398→          <strong>Community Resilience to Pandemics</strong> (above) and <strong>Social Resources and Community Resilience in the Wake of Disasters</strong><br>
399→          Cagney, K.A. et al. (2016) &mdash; <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0160824" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PLOS ONE</a><br>
400→          Introduces the Resilience Activation Framework, focusing on how access to social resources (formal and informal support) activates resilience capacities; useful for making &ldquo;social infrastructure&rdquo; measurable.<sup><a href="#fn14" id="fnref14" class="fn-ref">[14]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn15" id="fnref15" class="fn-ref">[15]</a></sup>
401→        </p>
402→
403→        <hr>
404→
405→        <!-- PERSONAL PSYCHOLOGICAL RESILIENCE -->
406→        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4" data-i18n="blog.resilience.h2.personal">Personal Psychological Resilience: Frameworks and Scales</h2>
407→
408→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p14">
409→          <strong>Resilience Resources, Coping Strategies and Positive Adaptation</strong><br>
410→          Fullerton, D.J. et al. (2021) &mdash; <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0246000" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PLOS ONE</a><br>
411→          Integrates several theoretical models (e.g., resilience as dynamic process) and tests a path model linking resilience resources, coping strategies, and outcomes; helpful for writing about mechanisms rather than traits.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1b" class="fn-ref">[1]</a></sup>
412→        </p>
413→
414→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p15">
415→          <strong>Conceptualizing and Measuring Psychological Resilience: What Can We Learn from Existing Models?</strong><br>
416→          (review article) &mdash; <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0732118X22000046" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect</a><br>
417→          Argues for defining psychological resilience in terms of dynamic responses to stressors and reviews measurement approaches, including outcome-based and process-based metrics.<sup><a href="#fn16" id="fnref16" class="fn-ref">[16]</a></sup>
418→        </p>
419→
420→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p16">
421→          <strong>A Conceptual Framework for the Neurobiological Study of Resilience</strong><br>
422→          Kalisch, R. et al. (2015) &mdash; <a href="https://www.biorxiv.org/lookup/external-ref?access_num=10.1017%2FS0140525X1400082X&amp;link_type=DOI" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">bioRxiv/PubMed</a><br>
423→          Proposes how to quantify resilience as relatively preserved mental health under stress, with implications for how to think about &ldquo;resilience as outcome&rdquo; in longitudinal terms.<sup><a href="#fn17" id="fnref17" class="fn-ref">[17]</a></sup>
424→        </p>
425→
426→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p17">
427→          <strong>The ART of Resilience: A Theoretical Bridge Across Approaches</strong><br>
428→          Frontiers in Psychology (2025) &mdash; <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2025.1556047/full" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Frontiers</a><br>
429→          Introduces the ART framework (Acknowledgment of resources, Reframing stressors, Tailoring responses) as a practical, process-oriented model that can be translated into everyday practices for individuals and groups.<sup><a href="#fn18" id="fnref18" class="fn-ref">[18]</a></sup>
430→        </p>
431→
432→        <hr>
433→
434→        <!-- COMPARISON TABLE -->
435→        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4" data-i18n="blog.resilience.h2.comparison">Community vs Personal Resilience: A Quick Comparison</h2>
436→
437→        <div class="table-wrap">
438→          <table>
439→            <thead>
440→              <tr>
441→                <th data-i18n="blog.resil.th1">Aspect</th>
442→                <th data-i18n="blog.resil.th2">Community / Neighborhood Resilience</th>
443→                <th data-i18n="blog.resil.th3">Personal Resilience</th>
444→              </tr>
445→            </thead>
446→            <tbody>
447→              <tr>
448→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td1"><strong>Core idea</strong></td>
449→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td2">Collective capacity to withstand, adapt, recover, and transform.<sup><a href="#fn2" id="fnref2c" class="fn-ref">[2]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn6" id="fnref6b" class="fn-ref">[6]</a></sup></td>
450→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td3">Individual&rsquo;s dynamic ability to maintain or regain functioning under stress.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1c" class="fn-ref">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn16" id="fnref16b" class="fn-ref">[16]</a></sup></td>
451→              </tr>
452→              <tr>
453→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td4"><strong>Typical frameworks</strong></td>
454→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td5">EnRiCH; IFRC; Resilience Activation; PEOPLES; pandemic resilience models.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="fnref6c" class="fn-ref">[6]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn7" id="fnref7b" class="fn-ref">[7]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn15" id="fnref15b" class="fn-ref">[15]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn10" id="fnref10b" class="fn-ref">[10]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn9" id="fnref9b" class="fn-ref">[9]</a></sup></td>
455→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td6">ART framework; resilience resources models; neurobiological resilience.<sup><a href="#fn18" id="fnref18b" class="fn-ref">[18]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1d" class="fn-ref">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn17" id="fnref17b" class="fn-ref">[17]</a></sup></td>
456→              </tr>
457→              <tr>
458→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td7"><strong>Common metrics</strong></td>
459→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td8">Indices across social, economic, infrastructure, environmental, governance dimensions.<sup><a href="#fn11" id="fnref11b" class="fn-ref">[11]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn3" id="fnref3c" class="fn-ref">[3]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn9" id="fnref9c" class="fn-ref">[9]</a></sup></td>
460→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td9">Scales like CD-RISC variants, coping patterns, mental health outcomes over time.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1e" class="fn-ref">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn16" id="fnref16c" class="fn-ref">[16]</a></sup></td>
461→              </tr>
462→              <tr>
463→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td10"><strong>Levers for change</strong></td>
464→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td11">Strengthening local networks, leadership, services, built environment, equity.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="fnref6d" class="fn-ref">[6]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn8" id="fnref8b" class="fn-ref">[8]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn7" id="fnref7c" class="fn-ref">[7]</a></sup></td>
465→                <td data-i18n="blog.resil.td12">Building coping skills, reframing, social support use, meaning-making.<sup><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1f" class="fn-ref">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href="#fn18" id="fnref18c" class="fn-ref">[18]</a></sup></td>
466→              </tr>
467→            </tbody>
468→          </table>
469→        </div>
470→
471→        <hr>
472→
473→        <p data-i18n="blog.resil.p18">
474→          These pieces should give you: (1) language for different meanings of &ldquo;resilience&rdquo;; (2) specific neighborhood-level frameworks you can narrate through stories or local examples; and (3) validated metrics you can reference or adapt into informal &ldquo;resilience audits&rdquo; for readers.
475→        </p>
